‘priest’, in particular a Christian priest. This surname is used among Christians, including Assyrians/Chaldeans. Compare   Cory  ,   Coury  ,   Cury  ,   Elkhoury  ,   Khouri  ,   Kory  ,   Koury  , and   Kury  ."]}]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adèle de Coucy was born in 1008, in Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Picardie, France, her father, Albéric de Coucy, was 28 and her mother, Adele de Roucy, was 20. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Dreux Drogon de Boves. She died in 1060, in Boves, Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1008–1060":"1008–1060","–Unknown":"Surnud","0998–1077":"0998–1077","1035–1116":"1035–1116","1060–1106":"1060–1106","–1076":"–1076","0980–1020":"0980–1020","0988–1049":"0988–1049","about 1060":"umbes 1060","1077":"1077","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1060":"1060","1008":"1008","1106":"1106","1116":"1116","1049":"1049","1035":"1035","0980":"0980","0998":"0998","0988":"0988","Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France":"Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Europa":"Europe","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England","Boves, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Boves, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1008–1060":"1008–1060","–Unknown":"Kuollut","0998–1077":"0998–1077","1035–1116":"1035–1116","1060–1106":"1060–1106","–1076":"–1076","0980–1020":"0980–1020","0988–1049":"0988–1049","about 1060":"noin 1060","1077":"1077","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1060":"1060","1008":"1008","1106":"1106","1116":"1116","1049":"1049","1035":"1035","0980":"0980","0998":"0998","0988":"0988","Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France":"Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Picardie, R